webpackJsonp([0xa0347e8d2456],{7076:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{post:{html:'<p>Why is it that any time Spiegel Online reports on a topic about which I have personal knowledge, they turn out to be completely full of shit? Latest case in point, <a href="http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/0,1518,324622,00.html" title="US-Wahlen in Deutschland: Marschbefehl zur Urne - Politik - SPIEGEL ONLINE">Marching Orders to Vote</a>, in which the Bush Administration is supposedly hindering civilian expats from voting. </p>\n<p>Bullshit. Thanks to the <a href="http://www.fvap.gov/">fvap.gov website</a>, it was never easier for me to arrange for my American absentee ballot than it was this year. I never had any problems reaching the site, <a href="http://www.blognewsnetwork.com/members/0000001/2004/09/23.html#a6620" title="Adam Curry\'s Weblog">even in September</a> when the story of problems first surfaced (i.e. Spiegel is a month late on this).</p>\n<p>Of course, the Medienkritiker are <a href="http://medienkritik.typepad.com/blog/2004/10/spiegel_online__5.html" title="Davids Medienkritik: SPIEGEL ONLINE: Marching Orders to Vote">calling Spiegel on this</a> as well.</p>',fields:{title:"Marching Orders to Vote",date:"25 Oct 2004",url:"https://papascott.de/2004-10-25-marching-orders-to-vote/"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/2004-10-25-marching-orders-to-vote/",prev:{fields:{title:"Don't Hit On Him",date:"25 Oct 2004",slug:"/2004-10-25-dont-hit-on-him/"}},next:{fields:{title:"Time is Money",date:"26 Oct 2004",slug:"/2004-10-26-time-is-money/"}}}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---2004-10-25-marching-orders-to-vote-a1e57805a518889cf7b7.js.map